from pyspark.sql import SparkSession
# Define the connection properties for Azure SQL database
# jdbc_hostname = 'server-rgda1.database.windows.net'
# jdbc_port = '1433'
# jdbc_database = 'azuresqldb_rgda1'
# jdbc_username = 'rgda1'
# jdbc_password = 'esspl@123'
# tableName='TrunkTable'
# tableName1='AppendTable'
# Create a SparkSession
spark = SparkSession.builder \
    .appName("RetrieveFromAzureSQL") \
    .getOrCreate()

# Define the JDBC connection properties
jdbc_url = "jdbc:sqlserver://server-rgda1.database.windows.net:1433;database=azuresqldb_rgda1"
jdbc_table = "[dbo].[product_table]"
jdbc_username = "rgda1"
jdbc_password = "esspl@123"

query = "SELECT * from [dbo].[datetime_data]"

# Read data from Azure SQL using the JDBC data source
df = spark.read \
    .format("jdbc") \
    .option("url", jdbc_url) \
    .option("dbtable", "(" + query + ") AS subquery") \
    .option("user", jdbc_username) \
    .option("password", jdbc_password) \
    .load()

query2 = "SELECT * from [dbo].[audit_test]"

# Read data from Azure SQL using the JDBC data source
df2 = spark.read \
    .format("jdbc") \
    .option("url", jdbc_url) \
    .option("dbtable", "(" + query2 + ") AS subquery") \
    .option("user", jdbc_username) \
    .option("password", jdbc_password) \
    .load()
